# Citation and Attribution

Standards for properly crediting sources and maintaining research integrity.

## Why Citation Matters

### For Credibility
- Claims without sources are just opinions
- Readers can verify your work
- Demonstrates thoroughness and rigor
- Distinguishes your analysis from others' work

### For Integrity
- Gives credit where due
- Avoids plagiarism
- Enables academic discourse
- Maintains trust in information ecosystem

### For Utility
- Readers can explore further
- Enables reproduction of research
- Creates knowledge trails
- Builds on collective understanding

## Citation Principles

### When to Cite

**Always cite:**
- Direct quotes
- Paraphrased ideas from specific sources
- Statistics and data
- Specific facts not commonly known
- Images, charts, or media from others
- Methodologies or frameworks developed by others

**No citation needed:**
- Common knowledge (Earth orbits the Sun)
- Your own original analysis
- General facts in your field's common understanding
- Your own observations and experiences

### What to Include

Minimum citation elements:
- Author(s) or organization
- Title of work
- Publication date
- Access date (for web sources)
- URL or DOI (for online sources)
- Page numbers (for specific quotes/data)

## Citation Formats

### Quick Reference Formats

**Web Article:**
```text
Author Last, First. "Article Title." Publication Name, Date Published. URL. Accessed Date.

Example:
Smith, John. "Market Trends 2025." Industry Weekly, January 15, 2025. https://example.com/article. Accessed February 3, 2026.
```

**Academic Paper:**
```text
Author Last, First, and Second Author. "Paper Title." Journal Name Vol, no. Issue (Year): Pages. DOI or URL.

Example:
Chen, Wei, and Sarah Johnson. "Machine Learning in Healthcare." Nature Medicine 15, no. 3 (2024): 234-256. https://doi.org/10.1038/example
```

**Book:**
```text
Author Last, First. Book Title. Publisher, Year.

Example:
Brown, Michael. Research Methods for Practitioners. Academic Press, 2023.
```

**Government/Institutional Report:**
```text
Organization. "Report Title." Report Number, Date. URL.

Example:
U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics. "Employment Situation Summary." USDL-25-0001, February 2025. https://bls.gov/report
```

**Interview/Personal Communication:**
```text
Name, Title at Organization. Interview by [Your Name], Date. [Method: phone, video, in-person].

Example:
Martinez, Elena, VP of Engineering at TechCorp. Interview by author, January 20, 2026. Video call.
```

### In-Text Citation Styles

**Direct Quote:**
> According to Smith, "the market grew by 15% in Q4" (Smith 2025, p. 12).

**Paraphrase:**
> Market growth accelerated significantly in the final quarter (Smith 2025).

**Multiple Sources:**
> Several studies support this conclusion (Smith 2025; Jones 2024; Chen et al. 2023).

**Conflicting Sources:**
> Smith (2025) argues for expansion, while Jones (2024) urges caution.

## Attribution in Practice

### Research Findings Attribution

```text
# Properly Attributed Finding

**Finding:** Customer acquisition costs increased 23% year-over-year.

**Source:** TechCo Q4 2025 Earnings Report, p. 15. Filed with SEC January 28, 2026.
**Verification:** Confirmed in analyst reports from Morgan Stanley (Jan 29, 2026) and Goldman Sachs (Jan 30, 2026).
**Confidence:** High (primary source + independent corroboration)
```

### Distinguishing Sources of Information

Use clear language to indicate origin:
- "According to [Source]..." - Direct attribution
- "Research indicates..." - Multiple sources support this
- "It has been reported that..." - Secondhand information
- "In my analysis..." - Your own work
- "Unverified reports suggest..." - Low-confidence information

### Handling Secondary Sources

When you can't access the original:

```text
Poor: "Einstein said 'imagination is more important than knowledge.'"
(Implies you read Einstein's original work)

Better: "Einstein reportedly said 'imagination is more important than knowledge,' as quoted in Smith's biography (Smith 2020, p. 45)."
(Acknowledges you're citing a secondary source)

Best: Find and cite the original source.
```

## Plagiarism Prevention

### What Constitutes Plagiarism

| Type | Description | Example |
|------|-------------|---------|
| **Direct** | Copying text without quotes or citation | Copying a paragraph verbatim |
| **Mosaic** | Mixing your words with uncited borrowed phrases | Slight rewording without citation |
| **Paraphrase** | Rewording ideas without attribution | Restating someone's argument as your own |
| **Self** | Reusing your own prior work without disclosure | Submitting same analysis twice |
| **Source** | Citing wrong source or fabricating citations | Citing paper you didn't read |

### Prevention Checklist

Before finalizing any research output:

- [ ] Every quote has quotation marks and citation
- [ ] Every paraphrase has attribution
- [ ] Statistics and data points have sources
- [ ] Borrowed frameworks/methodologies are credited
- [ ] Secondary sources are identified as such
- [ ] Your own analysis is clearly distinguished
- [ ] All citations are accurate and accessible

### Paraphrasing Guidelines

**Acceptable Paraphrase:**
1. Read and understand the original
2. Set the original aside
3. Write the idea in your own words
4. Compare to original to ensure sufficient difference
5. Add citation

**Unacceptable Paraphrase:**
- Changing a few words while keeping structure
- Using synonyms for key terms
- Rearranging sentences
- Combining phrases from original into new sentences

