│   ├── Author(s)
│   ├── Publication date
│   ├── Source type
│   └── URL/DOI
├── Access Information
│   ├── Date accessed
│   ├── How obtained (public, subscription, request)
│   └── Archived copy (if applicable)
├── Quality Assessment
│   ├── Credibility tier (1-5)
│   ├── Bias assessment
│   └── Verification status
├── Content Summary
│   ├── Key claims relevant to research
│   ├── Useful quotes (with page numbers)
│   └── Data points extracted
└── Usage Tracking
    ├── Where cited in your work
    └── How used (background, key evidence, etc.)
```

## Citation Ethics

### Accurate Representation

- Don't cite sources you haven't read
- Don't misrepresent what sources say
- Include context that might qualify claims
- Cite the actual source of an idea, not just a convenient one

### Conflict of Interest Disclosure

When citing sources:
- Note if source has obvious bias relevant to the claim
- Disclose if you have relationship with author/organization
- Flag if source is funded by interested parties

### Acknowledging Limitations

In your own work:
- Note when sources are limited or conflicting
- Acknowledge gaps in available evidence
- Be clear about what your sources do and don't support

## Common Citation Errors

### Citation Padding

Wrong: Add citations to appear thorough without actually supporting the claim.

Right: Every citation should directly support the specific claim it's attached to.

### Orphan Statistics

Wrong: "Studies show that 73% of customers prefer..."
(Which studies? When? What methodology?)

Right: "According to a 2025 McKinsey survey of 1,200 retail customers, 73% preferred..." (McKinsey 2025, p. 8)

### Stale Citations

Wrong: Cite a 2010 source for current market conditions.

Right: Use recent sources for current facts; historical sources only for historical context.

### Access Barrier Ignorance

Wrong: Cite paywalled source knowing readers can't verify.

Right: Note access requirements; prefer open-access when available; archive key sources.
